<http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/resource/monument_record_no/742M> <http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/definition/monument_desc> "Ames, Wright & Clayfield's Sugar House, located between Stone Bridge and Host Street.\r\nThe drawings [what drawings would those be John?] show a massive building of perhaps 7 storeys, of which 5 and an attic storey are depicted. The south-east elevation a 7 or 9-window range, the attic wall gabled at each end, but otherwise horizontal, hiding the gables behind. South-west elevation capped by a large chimney or hoist-housing, the main wall a 5-window(?) range with some blank bays.\r\nThe surgar house was occupied by Ames, Wright & Clayfield in 1824 (Braikenridge notes, D.41)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> <http://datadock.io/kal/local_data_1/id/dataset/Bristol_Monuments.csv>.
